When the two-digit integer $``\text{AB}"$ is cubed, the value is $912,\!673$. What is $A + B$?
inference:
Let $A$ and $B$ be the digits of the two-digit integer $``\text{AB}"$.
Then,

$$\text{AB}^3 = 912,\!673$$$$\Rightarrow\qquad A^3\cdot10^2 + 3\cdot A^2\cdot B\cdot10 + 3\cdot A\cdot B^2 + B^3 = 912,\!673$$$$\Rightarrow\qquad A^3\cdot10^2 + 30\cdot A^2\cdot B + 3\cdot A\cdot B^2 + B^3 = 912,\!673$$

Since $912,\!673$ is divisible by $9$, the left-hand side of the above equation must also be divisible by $9$.
This is possible only if $A + B + 3$ is divisible by $9$.
The only possible values of $A + B + 3$ that are less than or equal to $18$ are $9$ and $18$.
Since $A + B \ne 0$, we have $A + B = \boxed{9}$.
Final Answer: $\boxed{9}$. I hope it is correct.
